    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned something about needing an escrow account for this house i'm looking at in toronto. i've never bought a place before so i'm kinda lost. can u explain what escrow actually is and why it's even used in the closing process?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Escrow, in the context of buying a house, is essentially a neutral, trusted third party holding funds and documents until all the conditions of the sale are met. Think of it like a highly secure, temporary holding pen for your money and the deed to the house. It's crucial because it protects both you, the buyer, and the seller, ensuring that the money doesn't go to the seller until you officially get the keys, and the house doesn't transfer ownership until the funds are verified. In a real estate transaction, the escrow agent manages the flow of funds and paperwork until the closing date.",
